<section class="section narrow">
  <h2>The premise</h2>
  <p>Goblin's Greed was a four-player co-op dungeon crawler — procedurally-generated rooms, GAS-driven combat, traps that wanted to ruin your day, and a goblin merchant at the end of every run who wanted to do the same. The systems were the most ambitious thing I'd ever built solo, and most of them worked.</p>
  <p>I shelved it in March 2026. Not because the scope had run away, and not because I'd hit a technical wall. I shelved it because the market had answered a question I should have asked sooner — and the answer was no.</p>
</section>

<div class="pull-quote">
  <blockquote>The hardest part of being a solo developer isn't building the thing. It's reading the market well enough to know which thing is worth building.</blockquote>
</div>

<hr class="rule"/>

<section class="cs-system">
  <div>
    <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--accent-gg);">System 01</p>
    <h3>Combat that survives the network</h3>
    <p>Combat ran on the Gameplay Ability System with custom ability tasks for everything from charged shots to chained combos. Server-authoritative, client-predicted where it mattered, and resilient enough that the multiplayer never felt like the bolted-on layer it usually is in solo dev co-op games.</p>
    <span class="cs-tag">GAS</span><span class="cs-tag">AbilityTasks</span><span class="cs-tag">Replication</span>
  </div>
